{
  "answer": "**The short anthem-like verse appears in *Bang-E-Dara Part 3* by Allama Iqbal, chapter 23 (\"Tarana-e-Milli\").**[^4]\n\nIt opens as follows:\n\n> From Chin to Arab lands, our story flows,  \n> The whole wide world's the home a Muslim knows.[^1]\n\nThe two apostrophes are:\n\n> O Garden of Andalusia, do you recall the day,  \n> When on your branches high our nest in safety lay?[^2]\n\n> O wave of Tigris, you remember us, you know,  \n> Your river tells our story in its flow.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23 \"Tarana-e-Milli\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-8a4681).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23 \"Tarana-e-Milli\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-dea2e4).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23 \"Tarana-e-Milli\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-0bd01b).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23 \"Tarana-e-Milli\" [/translation/](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/).",
